# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carlton-football-club
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] The **1870 Victorian football season** was the inaugural senior premiership season of Australian rules football in the colony of Victoria.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] The competition was played during the winter of 1870, consisting of matches between metropolitan football clubs in Melbourne.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] The premier club was Melbourne, while Albert Park was the disputed winner of the Challenge Cup.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] The convention of 1870 being the inaugural premiership was applied retrospectively: in 1889, *The Argus* newspaper first published a table of historical premiers, and second and third-placed teams, dating back to 1870.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] In the article adjoining the 1889 table, it was commented that the haphazard nature of scheduling, frequency of cancelled matches, and overall lower standard of play made it difficult to assign a premiership for the seasons played between 1858 and 1869.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] The VFL's official publication, the *Football Record*, also showed this table from its inception in 1912 until 1918.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] From 1919 to 1923, this table was replaced with a table that showed the top four club placings since 1897, and two supplementary tables showing cumulated placings for the periods 1897-1918 and 1870-1918.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] These supplementary tables were omitted from the 1924 editions of the Record, and did not reappear after that.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] Since 2016, the AFL Commission has formally recognised the highest level of Victorian football back to 1870 as senior: this applies to both the unaffiliated era from 1870 to 1876 and the Victorian Football Association era from 1877 to 1896.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] In September 2025, the matter of the statistics and achievements from the 1870-1896 seasons reached the AFL Heritage Committee: the approval of the AFL Commission is required before any official changes are made to the AFL's records.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] Five clubs participated in senior football during the 1870 season: the city's principal clubs (Albert-park, Carlton, Melbourne and South Yarra), and a new club representing the Hobson's Bay Railway, which was playing its first season of senior football after three years of competing at junior level.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] The five clubs competed in specific matches for the Challenge Cup, and for the premiership (based on all matches played during the season).
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] In 1870, the South Yarra Football Club purchased and put up a new trophy, known as the Challenge Cup (sometimes as the *South Yarra Presentation Challenge Cup* to differentiate it from previous challenge cups donated by different organisations), for competition.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] South Yarra was the permanent holder of the previous Challenge Cup, having won it in 1866, and decided it would be appropriate to provide a new trophy for competition.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] Other stipulations relating to Challenge Cup games were that they were required to be controlled by central umpires, rather than by the team captains, and that no player was allowed to play for more than one club in Challenge Cup games during the year.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] Albert-park took possession of the Cup in the first game against South Yarra, and never relinquished it.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] However, the fate of the Cup became controversial when Hobson's Bay Railway forfeited its 11 June match against Albert-park due to lack of players: Railway declined to play when only fourteen of its selected twenty turned up on the day of the match.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] Conventionally, such a game would simply be considered a no-contest, but with the Challenge Cup at stake, Albert-park took to the field and scored two goals against no opposition as a formality and claimed a walkover victory.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] Having counted the walkover as its second Cup win, Albert-park subsequently claimed permanent possession of the Cup with its fourth win of the year on 20 August.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] However, the walkover victory was not recognised by South Yarra (as cup donors) or the other clubs, who all argued that the match was a no-contest rather than an Albert-park victory, and that another win was required to claim permanent ownership of the Cup.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] Albert-park argued that enough procedural requirements, such as the appointment of umpires and the pre-game coin toss, had been carried out for the game to be considered official, while Railway denied that these procedures had been carried out.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] Albert-park also argued that it was entitled to claim victory because Railway had declined the options of playing short or fielding other club officials or members who were present.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] Ultimately, the dispute was unresolved: there was no central body which could make a binding ruling on whether or not the walkover counted as a victory, and neither side conceded its opponent's point.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] Albert-park played only one further game for the season, a draw against Melbourne, but it refused to put the Cup up for contest in that match.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] Albert-park was denied the chance to become the undisputed permanent holder of the Cup on 6 August, when its return match with the weak Railway club was cancelled due to inclement weather.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] Albert-park ultimately gave the Cup back to South Yarra at the end of the year, but maintained its position that it had won the Cup outright and was donating it in its capacity as the Cup's owner.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] South Yarra maintained its position that Albert-park had not won the Cup, and had forfeited its position as incumbent holder.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] The following table lists the final results of all Challenge Cup games.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] Although it had claimed the Challenge Cup and was undefeated during the season, Albert-park was not recognised as premier club for 1870: instead, Melbourne, which was also undefeated, was the premier.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] The following table shows the five clubs' senior results during the year: all matches played among the five Challenge Cup teams, plus matches that Melbourne played against the Police and against the 18th Royal Irish Regiment.
[src:carlton-football-club/1870-victorian-football-season] Albert-park's disputed walkover victory against Railway is not included in the table.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] The **1871 Victorian football season** was the second senior season of Australian rules football in the colony of Victoria.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] Carlton was the premier club for first time, and it also won the Challenge Cup.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] Four clubs participated in senior football during the 1871 season: Albert-park, Carlton, Melbourne and South Yarra.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] Hobson's Bay Railway folded at the conclusion of the 1870 season.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] The formal practice of senior clubs playing matches *at odds* against junior clubs was established during the season.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] In matches played at odds, the senior team fielded fifteen players and the junior team fielded twenty players.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] Matches played at odds were quite competitive: the premier club Carlton was unbeaten at even strength against senior clubs, but lost two of five matches played at odds.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] Three metropolitan junior clubs – Collingwood, Richmond and Carlton United – played against the senior clubs during the year.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] Senior clubs also played matches against provincial clubs Ballarat (at odds) and Geelong (even strength) during the year.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] During the 1871 season, the senior clubs competed in specific matches for the Challenge Cup; and, separately, a premier team was selected based on all matches during the season, including Challenge Cup matches.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] The Challenge Cup which South Yarra had put up for contest at the start of the 1870 season was returned by Albert-park to South Yarra at the end of the year, following the dispute over whether or not Albert-park had formally won it.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] South Yarra opted to put the trophy up for contest again in 1871.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] Albert-park declined to contest it, although it continued to play senior games against the other clubs.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] The remaining clubs – Carlton, Melbourne and South Yarra – decided that each club would play the others three times during the season, and the top two would play a single playoff match for the Cup.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] This meant that the Cup was being contested in a league-type competition, and by traditional definitions was no longer a Challenge Cup with a perpetual holder.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] Two of the three Carlton-Melbourne matches were postponed by four weeks due to rain, while the two unplayed Carlton-South Yarra matches were scratched.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] With this victory in the playoff match, Carlton claimed undisputed and permanent ownership of the South Yarra Challenge Cup, and also won the 1871 premiership.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] In addition to winning the Challenge Cup, Carlton was adjudged premiers for the season, and Melbourne were runners-up.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] Albert-park was third: while they lost their matches against Carlton and Melbourne, they beat South Yarra (who had been winless since 1868 in senior matches) twice during the year.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] Carlton's and Melbourne's overall records as reported at each club's Annual General Meeting in 1872 (reporting different results for the disputed match between the teams) are given below.
[src:carlton-football-club/1871-victorian-football-season] The Senior results include the Challenge Cup playoff match, and matches Carlton and Melbourne played against Geelong.
[src:carlton-football-club/1872-victorian-football-season] The **1872 Victorian football season** was the third senior season of Australian rules football in the colony of Victoria.
[src:carlton-football-club/1872-victorian-football-season] Melbourne was the premier club for the second time.
[src:carlton-football-club/1872-victorian-football-season] Four metropolitan clubs participated in senior football during the 1872 season: Albert-park, Carlton, Melbourne and South Yarra.
[src:carlton-football-club/1872-victorian-football-season] Geelong and Ballarat also played, but since they played too few games, they are not listed with the metropolitan clubs below.
[src:carlton-football-club/1872-victorian-football-season] Melbourne was the premier club for the season, with Carlton runners-up.
[src:carlton-football-club/1872-victorian-football-season] The two clubs were the dominant senior clubs in the colony, and the premiership was mostly determined based on the head-to-head record in matches between the two: their four matches yielded two wins for Melbourne, one win for Carlton and one draw.
[src:carlton-football-club/1872-victorian-football-season] Albert-park was placed third, its only win coming against South Yarra, who once again failed to win a game against any of the other principal clubs.
[src:carlton-football-club/1872-victorian-football-season] There was no Challenge Cup contested by the senior clubs during the 1872 season, but in the junior competition, a Junior Challenge Cup was established, contested and paid for equally by the four leading junior clubs: Collingwood, East Melbourne, Richmond and Southern.
[src:carlton-football-club/1872-victorian-football-season] The cup was contested as a round-robin amongst the four teams, with each club playing the others twice, earning two premiership points for a win and one for a draw.
[src:carlton-football-club/1872-victorian-football-season] Richmond won the cup with eight points; Collingwood was second with seven points; East Melbourne was third with six points; and Southern was fourth with three points.
[src:carlton-football-club/1872-victorian-football-season] The junior clubs played several games at odds against the seniors, with the seniors usually fielding sixteen men to the juniors' twenty, compared with fifteen-to-twenty in 1871.
[src:carlton-football-club/1872-victorian-football-season] The following table shows the clubs' senior results during the year amongst the four Challenge Cup teams, plus matches Carlton played against Geelong and Ballarat, and a match South Yarra played against Geelong.
[src:carlton-football-club/1872-victorian-football-season] Matches played against junior clubs and/or at odds are not included in the table.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] The **1873 Victorian football season** was the fourth senior season of Australian rules football in the colony of Victoria.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] Carlton was the premier club for the second time.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] A number of football clubs were formed in Victoria in for the 1873 season, including St Kilda, which was officially established on 2 April 1873.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] Four metropolitan clubs participated in senior football during the 1873 season: Albert Park, Carlton, Melbourne and University, although University played too few games and its record is not shown below.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] Notable for its absence was South Yarra, which folded in July 1873 after being a powerhouse of the 1860s.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] Many of its players went to the newly-established and nearby St Kilda Football Club, which was elevated to senior ranks in 1874.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] Carlton and Melbourne were considered the dominant clubs in the city, so the premier club was decided based entirely on the head-to-head record between the clubs.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] In their four meetings, Carlton won two matches and the other two were drawn, meaning Carlton was recognised as the season's premier club.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] The below table shows the results for senior clubs during the 1873 season across all matches (senior, junior, and at odds), excluding abandoned matches played by Carlton against Albert Park and University.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] Geelong was the strongest provincial team, being undefeated in provincial matches and suffering its only loss of the season against Melbourne.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] According to the official tables published in *The Argus* from 1889 and in the *Football Record* from 1912 to 1923, Geelong was the third-placed club in the Victorian premiership in 1873.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] Of the 12 junior clubs that competed at a relatively even standard – Carlton Imperial, Collingwood, East Melbourne, Essendon, Hawthorn, North Melbourne, Richmond, St Kilda, Southern, South Park, Studley Park and Williamstown – none managed an unbeaten record in matches against the other juniors.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] The numbers advantage to juniors clubs in matches at odds against senior clubs was reduced in 1873, with the junior club usually fielding 20 men to the senior club's 18.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] It has been rumoured that bushranger Ned Kelly played 11 games for Williamstown during the 1873 season.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] The claim was supported by Williamstown's longest-servving club president, Trevor Monti, who said in 2014 that Kelly was on track to win the club's best and fairest before he was reported for headbutting an umpire in his last game.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] The claim has been disputed, as Kelly was only known to be in the Williamstown area for six months in 1873 as a prisoner.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] In 1928, the club discovered a prototype of the armour that Kelly later used during his last stand in 1880.
[src:carlton-football-club/1873-victorian-football-season] Although there was no clear premier junior club for the 1873 season, a rough ladder includes North Melbourne and Southern as some of the best-performing teams.
[src:carlton-football-club/1874-victorian-football-season] The **1874 Victorian football season** was the fifth senior season of Australian rules football in the colony of Victoria.
[src:carlton-football-club/1874-victorian-football-season] Carlton was the premier club for the third time.
[src:carlton-football-club/1874-victorian-football-season] A number of football clubs were formed in Victoria for the 1874 season, including South Melbourne, which was incorporated on 19 June 1874.
[src:carlton-football-club/1874-victorian-football-season] It was first known as "Cecil Football Club", but adopted the name "South Melbourne Football Club" four weeks later on 15 July.
[src:carlton-football-club/1874-victorian-football-season] Five metropolitan clubs participated in senior football during the 1874 season: Albert Park, Carlton, Melbourne, North Melbourne and St Kilda.
[src:carlton-football-club/1874-victorian-football-season] North Melbourne and St Kilda were newly elevated from junior ranks to senior ranks for this season, while University – which was a senior club in 1873 but only played a minimal number of games – instead played in the Second Twenty competition.
[src:carlton-football-club/1874-victorian-football-season] Carlton, which was undefeated during the season, was considered the premier club, with Melbourne runners-up, mostly by virtue of Carlton winning all four matches it played against Melbourne during the season.
[src:carlton-football-club/1874-victorian-football-season] Melbourne had a slightly better record against the remaining senior clubs (Melbourne having a record of 6-1-1 to Carlton's record of 5-0-5), but such was Carlton's and Melbourne's dominance at the time that their matches against the other clubs had little influence on the premiership.
[src:carlton-football-club/1874-victorian-football-season] The below table is set of results for senior clubs during the 1874 season across all matches, including those against senior, junior and intercolonial clubs.
[src:carlton-football-club/1874-victorian-football-season] Tables published in *The Argus* from 1889 and in the *Football Record* from 1912 to 1923 listed St Kilda as the third-placed club in 1874, but contemporary sources dispute this.
[src:carlton-football-club/1874-victorian-football-season] Geelong was the best performing provincial team of the 1874 season.
[src:carlton-football-club/1874-victorian-football-season] It was undefeated in provincial matches, and it held the newly established Western District Challenge Cup throughout the season, but lost three matches against metropolitan clubs.
[src:carlton-football-club/1874-victorian-football-season] Some sources from 1874 place Geelong in fourth (across all matches) or fifth (only matches against senior clubs) out of six clubs.
[src:carlton-football-club/1874-victorian-football-season] Other known provincial teams in 1874 include Barwon, Kardinia, and Phoenix Foundry.
[src:carlton-football-club/1874-victorian-football-season] East Melbourne was the best performing junior club in 1874, winning nine of its 18 matches.
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] The **1875 Victorian football season** was the sixth senior season of Australian rules football in the colony of Victoria.
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] Carlton was the premier metropolitan club for the fourth time, while Geelong was the premier provincial club.
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] Seven metropolitan clubs participated in senior football during the 1875 season: Albert Park, Carlton, Carlton Imperial, East Melbourne, Melbourne, North Melbourne and St Kilda cum University (a combined St Kilda and Melbourne University team).
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] As had been the case for several years, Carlton and Melbourne were considered the dominant clubs in the city, so the premier club was decided based entirely on the head-to-head record between the clubs.
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] In their four meetings, Carlton won three and Melbourne won one, so Carlton was recognised as the premier club for the season.
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] A Challenge Cup played as a double round-robin amongst the second twenties (reserves teams) of the senior clubs was staged during the season.
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] The Cup was won by Carlton Imperial, after it defeated Albert Park 1–0 in the final on 9 October.
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] The table shows the results for senior clubs during the 1875 season across all matches, including senior, junior and odds matches.
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] Clubs are listed in the order in which they were ranked in *The Australasian* newspaper.
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] Other than announcing the top three place-getters, there was no formal process by which the clubs were ranked, so the below order should be considered indicative only (particularly because the fixturing of matches was not standardised).
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] Geelong were premiers in the provincial competition.
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] Other senior provincial clubs in 1875 included Ballarat, Ballarat Imperial, Beechworth, Castlemaine, Inglewood, Rochester and South Ballarat.
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] In addition to the premiership, Geelong became the permanent owners of the Western District Challenge Cup, which it had held since the start of 1874.
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] The club won the cup after its controversial win against Ballarat on 25 September at the Argyle Ground in Geelong.
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] In the match, Austin of Geelong, while in possession of the ball, weaved through several spectators who were encroaching on the playing field, before passing to Fairbain who kicked a goal.
[src:carlton-football-club/1875-victorian-football-season] Ballarat protested against the goal based on interference, and when the goal was upheld, walked off the ground and forfeited the match.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] The **1876 Victorian football season** was the seventh senior season of Australian rules football in the colony of Victoria.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] Melbourne was the premier metropolitan club for the third time, while Barwon was the premier provincial club.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] This was the final season of decentralised administration of football in Victoria, with the Victorian Football Association (VFA) formed the following year to provide a committee-based approach to the administration of the sport.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] In May 1876, shortly before the start of the season, the North Melbourne Football Club was disbanded, and most senior players and many members of the club joined the Albert-park Football Club, which was itself in a weakened position due to the departure of many players.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] The arrangement lasted only for one year, and the Hotham Football Club was re-established in North Melbourne in 1877.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] Six metropolitan clubs participated in senior football during the 1876 season: Albert Park, Carlton, Carlton Imperial, East Melbourne, Melbourne and St Kilda.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] Albert Park won the Second Twenties' Challenge Cup, while Williamstown was the leading junior club and won the Junior Challenge Cup.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] Baker had taken a mark right on the goal line and quickly kicked the ball between the posts, despite protests by Carlton players that Baker had illegally pushed Carlton defender Harry Nudd out of the marking contest.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] However, Searcy was offended by the language that the Carlton players had used toward him and instead left the ground immediately, without having resolved the issue of the goal.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] There was a delay of fifteen minutes before a new umpire, Bride, could be found, during which Carlton unsuccessfully protested the awarding of the goal.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] Each club scored one additional goal during the rest of the game, resulting in a 2–1 victory for Melbourne.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] Following the match, Carlton maintained its position of disputing Baker's goal, and claimed the match as a 1–1 draw; with no formal means of resolving the dispute, both clubs maintained their positions to the point that the two clubs reported different results for the match in their annual reports.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] The below table shows the results for senior clubs during the 1876 season.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] The list shows the club records across all matches, including senior, junior and odds matches.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] In the provincial competition, Barwon was the premier team, and was the winner of the Geelong, Ballarat and Wimmera District Challenge Cup.
[src:carlton-football-club/1876-victorian-football-season] Barwon was presented with the cup after defeating Geelong 2–1 on 29 July.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The **Carlton Football Club**, nicknamed the **Blues**, is a professional Australian rules football club based at Princes Park in Carlton North, an inner suburb of Melbourne in Victoria, Australia.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The club competes in the Australian Football League (AFL), the sport's premier competition.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Founded in the 1860s, the club began playing out of parklands historically part of Carlton not far from its current base.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] It quickly became one of the major football clubs in the city.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] It was a foundation member of the Victorian Football Association (VFA), winning the inaugural premiership in 1877.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] In 1896, Carlton joined the breakaway Victorian Football League (since renamed the AFL), and alongside rivals Collingwood, Essendon and Richmond is regarded as one of the league's historical "Big Four" clubs, with 16 VFL/AFL premierships (a joint record with Collingwood and Essendon).
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The club's AFL Women's team has competed since the league's inaugural 2017 AFLW season.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] It currently plays its home matches at Docklands Stadium and the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Princes Park is its traditional home ground of the club and is home to its women's team.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton also has reserves sides in the Victorian Football League and VFL Women's.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] During a meeting on 17 May 1865 at the University Hotel in Grattan Street Carlton the Carlton Football Club nominated secretary Ben James and president James Linacre respectively.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The club formally adopted the Melbourne Football Club rules.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] This is the earliest record of incorporation however the club believes it was formed earlier based on numerous indirect accounts and officially celebrates anniversaries based on a foundation date of 1864.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] It also continues to investigate evidence of an earlier foundation, including the proposed formation of a Carlton Football Club on 21 May 1861 connected to a Carlton Cricket Club.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The earliest records of the club playing were from 1865 out of Princes Park in Carlton.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] In the early days, Carlton became particularly strong competitively and grew a large supporter base.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] It became a fierce rival to the Melbourne Football Club in early competitions, including the South Yarra Challenge Cup, and the club is recognised as senior Victorian premiers in 1871, 1873, 1874 and 1875.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] In 1877, Carlton was one of the foundation clubs of the Victorian Football Association, and was a comfortable winner of the premiership in the competition's inaugural season.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton was one of the first clubs to have a player worthy of the superstar tag: champion player George Coulthard, who played for Carlton between 1876 and 1882, and was noted by *The Australasian* as 'The grandest player of the day'.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] He died of tuberculosis in 1883, aged 27.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The club won one more VFA premiership, in 1887, but after that, particularly during the 1890s, the club went from one of the strongest clubs in the Association to one of the weaker, both on-field and off-field.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] In spite of this, the club was invited to join the breakaway Victorian Football League competition in 1897.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The club continued to struggle in early seasons of the new competition, and finished seventh out of eight teams in each of its first five seasons.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton's fortunes improved significantly in 1902.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The Board elected the highly respected former Fitzroy footballer and Australian test cricketer Jack Worrall, then the secretary of the Carlton Cricket Club, to the same position at the football club.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] As secretary, Worrall slowly took over the managing of the players, in what is now recognised as the first official coaching role in the VFL.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Under Worrall's guidance in the latter part of the 1902 season, Carlton's on-field performances improved, and in 1903 he led Carlton to the finals for the first time.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton built a strong reputation and financial position, and was able to convince many great players to shift to the club from other clubs, or even (in the case of Mick Grace) out of retirement.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Worrall led the club to its first three VFL premierships, won consecutively, in 1906, 1907 and 1908.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Following these premierships, Carlton went through a tumultuous period off-field.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Some players had become frustrated by low payments and hard training standards, and responded by refusing to train or even play matches.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The club removed Worrall from the coaching role (he retained the role of secretary), and after significant changes at board level after the 1909 season, Worrall left the club altogether.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Many players who had supported Worrall left the club at the end of the season.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Then, in 1910, several players were suspected of having taken bribes to fix matches, with two players (Alex Lang and Doug Fraser) both found guilty and suspended for 99 matches.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Despite this backdrop, Carlton continued its strong on-field form, reaching the 1909 and 1910 Grand Finals, but losing both.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton fell out of the finals in 1913, but returned in 1914 under coach Norm Clark, and with many inexperienced players, to win back-to-back premierships in 1914 and 1915 VFL seasons.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Most football around the country was suspended during the height of World War I, but Carlton continued to compete in a VFL which featured, at its fewest, only four clubs.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Altogether, between Jack Worrall's first Grand Final in 1904 and the peak of World War I in 1916, Carlton won five premierships and contested nine Grand Finals for one of the most successful times in the club's history.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The only success which eluded the club was the Championship of Australia; Carlton contested the championship three times (1907, 1908 and 1914), with its South Australian opponents victorious on all three occasions.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Through the 1920s and the Great Depression of the 1930s, Carlton maintained a strong on-field presence.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The club was a frequent finalist, contesting fourteen finals series between the wars.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] However, premiership success did not follow, and the club contested only three Grand Finals for just one premiership during this period, and endured the second longest premiership drought (23 years) in the club's history.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The drought was broken with the club's sixth VFL premiership in 1938, when former Subiaco and South Melbourne champion Brighton Diggins was recruited by the club to serve as captain-coach.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] On-field, Carlton's inter-war period was highlighted by two of its greatest goalkickers: in the 1920s, Horrie Clover (396 goals in 147 games), and in the 1930s, Harry "Soapy" Vallence (722 goals in 204 games), both of which were Carlton career records at the time.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The VFL continued to operate through World War II.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] With the retirement of Diggins, Carlton secured the services of former Richmond coach Percy Bentley, who coached the club for fifteen seasons.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton continued to finish in or near the finals without premiership success through the war, before winning the premiership in 1945, one month after peace.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton contested two more Grand Finals in the 1940s, both against Essendon, winning the 1947 Grand Final by a single point, and being comfortably beaten in 1949.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Thereafter followed what was then Carlton's weakest on-field period since Worrall's appointment in 1902, with the club reaching the finals only four times between 1950 and 1964.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Finishing tenth out of twelve and winning only five matches, 1964 was Carlton's worst VFL season to that point in its history.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] A change of president at the end of 1964 heralded the most successful period in the Carlton Football Club's history.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Between 1967 and 1988, Carlton missed the finals only three times, contested ten Grand Finals, and won seven premierships.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The period of success began when George Harris replaced Lew Holmes as president of the club, after the 1964 season.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Harris then signed Melbourne legend Ron Barassi serve as coach from 1965.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Barassi was a six-time premiership player and two-time premiership captain at Melbourne during its most successful era, and at the age of 28 was still one of the biggest names in the game.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] His shift to Carlton remains one of the biggest player transfers in the game's history.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Also contributing to Carlton's success was the strength of the Bendigo Football League, to which Carlton gained recruitment access through the VFL's country zoning arrangements.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Under Barassi, Carlton reached three consecutive Grand Finals between 1968 and 1970, resulting in two premierships: 1968 against Essendon and 1970 against traditional rivals Collingwood.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The 1970 Grand Final remains one of the most famous matches in football history.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton won its first and second Championship of Australia titles in 1968 and 1970, beating the SANFL's Sturt Football Club in both seasons.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton missed the finals in 1971, and Barassi left the club at the end of the season, but Carlton returned to prominence the following year, and contested back-to-back Grand Finals.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Both matches were against Richmond, with Carlton recording a high-scoring victory in 1972, and losing a rough, physical encounter in 1973.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Of the legendary players from the Barassi era, none was more important than John Nicholls, who captained all three premierships and took over as captain-coach upon Barassi's departure.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Nicholls, a ruckman and forward, had played at Carlton since 1957, and he and Graham Farmer (who played with Geelong and in the WAFL during the same era) are regarded as the greatest ruckmen in the league's history.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Midfielders Sergio Silvagni and Adrian Gallagher, half-forward Robert Walls, and ruckman Percy Jones were also prominent throughout the Barassi era, and in 1970, Alex Jesaulenko became the first (and to date, only) Carlton forward to kick 100 goals in a season.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton continued to play finals through the 1970s without premiership success, and went through several coaches in a short period of time: Nicholls (until 1975), Ian Thorogood (1976–77), Ian Stewart (for only three matches in 1978), and Alex Jesaulenko as playing coach after Stewart's departure.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] It was not until 1979 that Carlton again reached the Grand Final, defeating Collingwood by five points in a close match best remembered for the late goal kicked by Ken Sheldon, after Wayne Harmes tapped the ball into the goalsquare from the boundary line.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] After the 1979 season, there was off-field instability at the board level.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Ian Rice replaced George Harris as president,N 2 and many of Harris' supporters left the club, including Jesaulenko, who went to St Kilda.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Percy Jones replaced Jesaulenko as coach in 1980, before Hawthorn coach David Parkin was recruited in 1981, Carlton's sixth coach in eight seasons.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Despite the off-field troubles, Carlton continued to thrive on-field, and Parkin led the team to back-to-back premierships in 1981 and 1982, with victories in the Grand Finals against Collingwood and Richmond respectively.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] With its fourteenth premiership in 1982, Carlton overtook Collingwood to become the most successful club in the league's history, based on premierships won – a position it has held either outright or jointly with Essendon and Collingwood since.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Starring on-field during this period for Carlton was Bruce Doull, regarded as one of the best half-back flankers in the history of the league.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Wayne Johnston was a prominent centreman/forward, and Carlton had great success recruiting high-profile Western Australian footballers to the club, including Mike Fitzpatrick, Ken Hunter and Peter Bosustow.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] In 1983, John Elliott took over the presidency from Ian Rice.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] On-field, the club endured three consecutive unsuccessful finals campaigns under Parkin before he was replaced by Robert Walls in 1986.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Also in 1986, Carlton lured three of South Australia's top young players to the club: Stephen Kernahan, Craig Bradley and Peter Motley.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The club reached the next two Grand Finals, losing in 1986 and winning in 1987, both times against Hawthorn.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Kernahan went on to become the club's longest serving captain and leading career goalkicker (738 goals), and Bradley became the club games record holder (375 games); Motley's career was unfortunately cut short by a non-fatal car accident in 1987.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton had also recruited Stephen Silvagni (son of Sergio) in 1985, who is now recognised as one of the greatest fullbacks of all time, and secured the league's star player Greg Williams in a trade in 1992.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] David Parkin returned to coach the club from 1991 until 2000, and Carlton was a mainstay of the finals throughout most of this time.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] In 1995, Carlton became the first team to win twenty matches in a home-and-away season (finishing with a record of 20–2), and won the Grand Final against Geelong to claim its sixteenth premiership.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] In 2002, Carlton swiftly fell from being one of the most successful clubs, both on-field and off-field, to one of the least successful.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] At the same time, the club was starting to struggle financially, due to unwise investments under John Elliott – most significantly, building a new grandstand at Princes Park during the 1990s, at a time when other clubs were finding it more profitable to play at the higher-capacity central venues.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Then, at the end of 2002, it was revealed that Carlton had been systematically cheating the league salary cap during the early 2000s.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The scandal resulted in the loss of draft picks and a fine of $930,000, which exacerbated the club's poor on-field and off-field positions.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] In the immediate fall-out from 2002, president John Elliott was voted out by the members, and was replaced with Docklands Stadium CEO Ian Collins.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Under Collins, the club shifted its home stadium from Princes Park to Docklands, with the final match played at Princes Park in 2005.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Additionally, coach Wayne Brittain was sacked, and replaced with Kangaroos coach Denis Pagan.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] On-field performances did not improve under Pagan, and overall the club won three wooden spoons and finished in the bottom two five times between 2002 and 2007.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Pagan was sacked as coach mid-season after a string of heavy defeats, and was replaced by former club captain and assistant coach Brett Ratten.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Then, prior to the 2008 season, Carlton was able to secure a trade for West Coast's Chris Judd, one of the league's best midfielders, to join the club as captain.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The time spent at the bottom of the ladder also allowed Carlton to secure three No.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] 1 draft picks – Marc Murphy, Bryce Gibbs and Matthew Kreuzer – who helped the club's on-field position.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Brett Ratten led Carlton to the finals from 2009 until 2011, but was sacked with a year remaining on his contract after the club missed the finals in 2012, and was replaced by former West Coast and Collingwood premiership coach Mick Malthouse.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Under Malthouse, the club returned to the finals in 2013, but fell to thirteenth in 2014.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Kernahan stepped aside in mid-2014, and was replaced by Mark LoGiudice, who presided over a period of mediocre onfield results.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The relationship between Malthouse and the club's quickly and publicly deteriorated; and in early 2015, after giving a radio interview critical of the board, Malthouse was sacked the club going on to finish last.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Bolton's replacement, David Teague, helped the club avoid the 2019 wooden spoon, but lasted only two years into a three-year contract without a finals appearance.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] LoGiudice handed over the presidency to Luke Sayers in August 2021, and Sayers conducted an extensive independent review of the football department during the second half of that season; Teague was sacked, and Michael Voss was appointed senior coach.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Voss led the club for just over four seasons, and led the club to finals in his second and third seasons, ending what had become a club-record nine year VFL/AFL finals drought, with his best result a preliminary final defeat in 2023.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] However, after a sharp downturn in performances starting in mid-2024, culminating in a 1–8 start to the 2026 season, Voss and the club parted ways early in the final year of his contract.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] During this time, Carlton achieved two of its greatest individual successes, with captain Patrick Cripps becoming the club's first dual Brownlow Medallist and full forward Charlie Curnow becoming the club's first back-to-back Coleman Medallist.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Sayers also stood down as president during this time, replaced by Robert Priestly in early 2025.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The current Carlton guernsey is navy blue, emblazoned with a white CFC monogram (which stands for "Carlton Football Club") on the front, and white numbers on the back.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] This guernsey design is specified in the club's constitution.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Other than changes to the font of the monogram, this has been Carlton's guernsey continually since 1909.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The club has worn navy blue in its uniform since 1871, when colour of the team's caps was changed from orange/yellow.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The club's on-and-off field apparel was manufactured by Nike from 1998 until 2019, and by Puma from 2020 until at least 2029.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The team wears navy blue shorts in home games, and white shorts in away games.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Since the introduction of clash guernseys in 2007, Carlton has had several clash designs which have been mostly white, with navy blue monogram, numbers, trimmings and minor panels in a variety of combinations.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Designs in predominantly sky blue (2011–2012) and silver (2018) have also been used.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton's official nickname is the 'Blues'.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Since the addition of navy blue to the playing uniform in 1871, the club has been known almost universally in print media as the Blues, Dark Blues or Navy Blues.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Other colloquial nicknames include Bluebaggers or 'Baggers.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Prior to 1871, when the uniform was predominantly chamois, the club was known informally as the Butchers.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] For a time after World War II, the club briefly considered changing its nickname to the Cockatoos, but this never formally eventuated; even so, the association with the nickname was strong enough that newspaper cartoons depicting a Carlton cockatoo were common.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The cockatoo connection derived from the talking cockatoo brought to home matches by club member Bob St.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Marr for more than 30 years; intelligent enough to squawk its support for Carlton and loud enough to be heard over the crowd, 'Cocky Marr' had become an unofficial live mascot for the club until the bird's death in 1939.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton's club song is *We Are the Navy Blues*.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The lyrics are believed to have been written in around 1930 by cousins Irene McEldrew and Agnes Wright, who ran a boarding house for several club players and the latter of whom was the niece of then-coach Dan Minogue.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] It is sung to the tune of *Lily of Laguna*.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The club's traditional home ground is Princes Park (currently known as Ikon Park), located in North Carlton.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] After struggling to find a permanent home venue during its time in the VFA, Carlton established Princes Park as its home venue when it joined the VFL in 1897.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The club played most of its home matches at Princes Park every year between 1897 and 2004 (except for 2002, when it played only four home games there), and a single farewell game was staged at the venue in 2005.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] It was the last of the suburban home groundsN 3 to be used in AFL competition.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The venue remains Carlton's training and administrative base, and the club's current 40-year lease on the venue with the City of Melbourne runs until 2035.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Since 2005, Carlton has split its home games between Docklands Stadium and the Melbourne Cricket Ground, with six matches at the former and five at latter in most years.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The matches expected to draw the highest crowds are usually scheduled for the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton possesses a long and bitter rivalry with Collingwood, with the rivalry considered to be one of the most historic and significant in Australian sport, dating back to their spiteful 1910 Grand Final.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] They have met six times in Grand Finals, with Carlton successful in all bar the first.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton home matches between the club contest the Richard Pratt Cup, and Collingwood home matches are designated as the **Peter Mac Cup**.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] They also share the same number of premierships, at 16.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] With 16 premierships apiece, the two teams, along with Collingwood, are the joint most successful teams in the VFL/AFL history.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Grand finals between the two clubs were played in 1908, 1947, 1949, 1962, 1968 and 1993, each team winning three of the six.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton has a rivalry with Richmond, with this rivalry based on geographical proximity and large supporter bases.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The two teams contested four grand finals between 1969 and 1982, each winning two; and since 2008 have met annually on a Thursday night in round 1 at the Melbourne Cricket Ground, usually as the opening game of the season.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Four emergencies were also named: (1) Laurie Kerr, (2) Bob Chitty, (3) Horrie Clover and (4) Rod McGregor.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The five players with an asterisk(*) are also members of the AFL Team of the Century – the largest number of any AFL club.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The Carlton Football Club established its Hall of Fame in 1987, with nine inaugural inductees.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Each year between 1988 and 2001 an additional three to five people were inducted into the Carlton Hall of Fame.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] After a five-year break, an additional ten people were inducted into the Hall of Fame in 2006.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] As of May 2016, there have been 77 inductees.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] A year after the AFL added a Legends category to the Australian Football Hall of Fame, Carlton added a Legends category to its hall of fame in 1997.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Twenty-five people have been inducted into the Australian Football Hall of Fame for their services to football for careers which were either partially or entirely served with the Carlton Football Club.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Of those, three have Legend status in the Hall of Fame.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Peter Bedford, Craig Bradley, Horrie Clover, George Coulthard, Bruce Doull, Ken Hands, Ern Henfry, Ken Hunter, Wayne Johnston, Chris Judd, Stephen Kernahan, Anthony Koutoufides, Rod McGregor, Peter McKenna, Stephen Silvagni, Geoff Southby, Harry Vallence, Robert Walls, Greg Williams.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Since 1978 the club has operated as the incorporated company Carlton Football Club Limited.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton's seconds/reserves team was established in 1919; it operated semi-independently of the senior club until 1936, when the senior club's committee fully took over its operations.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] From 1919 to 1991 the VFL/AFL operated a reserves competition, and from 1992 to 1999 a *de facto* AFL reserves competition was run by the Victorian State Football League.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The Carlton Football Club fielded a reserves team in both of these competitions, allowing players who were not selected for the senior team to play for Carlton in the lower grade.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Following the demise of the AFL reserves competition, the Carlton reserves team competed in the new Victorian Football League for three seasons from 2000 until 2002.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The reserves team was dissolved at the end of 2002, and Carlton entered a reserves affiliation with existing VFL club, the Northern Bullants.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Under the affiliation, reserves players for Carlton played VFL football with the Northern Bullants.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton terminated the affiliation with the Northern Blues in early 2020, as a cost saving measure during the COVID-19 pandemic, and re-established a dedicated reserves team in the VFL for the 2021 season.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Under the AFL's 2016 plan to establish club-branded Next Generation Academies across Australia to give all AFL clubs a more active role in junior development, Carlton was allocated the northern metropolitan zone of Melbourne.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The academy is linked to the Preston-based Northern Knights in the statewide under-18s system.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Since 2019, the club has operated the Carlton College of Sports, a higher education institution in partnership with La Trobe University, which offers sports education diplomas and is operated out of the redeveloped grandstands at Ikon Park.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The Carlton Football Club operates two senior women's teams: one team in the national AFL Women's competition, which it has fielded since the 2017 AFLW season; and one team in the state VFL Women's competition, which has been fielded since the 2018 VFLW season.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Carlton was a key cog in the establishment of Women's football in the state of Victoria.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] In August 1933 the club hosted the first ever VFL sanctioned match between women's teams, with sides representing Carlton and Richmond.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Though Richmond's side was not associated directly with the VFL club of the same name, the Carlton side was picked and trained by the club with VFL players Mickey Crisp and Ray Brew as coaches.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The match, played at Carlton's home Princes Park drew an estimated crowd of 10,000 and raised funds as part of a VFL bye-week carnival for The Royal Melbourne Hospital.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The club next fielded a women's team more than a decade later when it competed in a 1947 charity exhibition series raising funds in support of food shortages in post-war Commonwealth countries.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The club's team played multiple matches in multiple series that season including a match against Footscray in July and a subsequent series against Hawthorn, South Melbourne, St Kilda and Footscray in August 1947.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] In June 2016, Carlton was granted a licence to establish and field a team in the eight team AFL Women's league, which was set to stage its inaugural season in February–March 2017.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The team is run and fully integrated within the Carlton Football Club, with football operation initially overseen by existing Head of Football Andrew McKay.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Damien Keeping served as the team's inaugural head coach, and the club's existing Female Football Ambassador, Lauren Arnell, served as the inaugural captain; she, along with Marquee players and Darcy Vescio and Brianna Davey were the club's inaugural marquee signings.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] In 2018, the Western Bulldogs and Carlton women's teams held the first Pride game in the AFLW, to celebrate gender diversity, promote inclusion for LGBTIQA+ players, and to help stamp out homophobia.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] After being joined by other clubs, in 2020, the first full AFLW Pride Round was held in 2021, supported by all 18 clubs in the league.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] In its history, the team has played in one grand final, which it lost against Adelaide in 2019.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] Prior the 2018 season, Carlton was granted a licence to field a team in the VFL Women's competition.
[src:carlton-football-club/carlton-football-club] The VFLW team originally operated under a separate program to the club's AFLW team, however in 2021 the VFLW was formally aligned with the AFLW competition, similar to the men's AFL/VFL system.
